Pop your kettle on to boil. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into ½cm pieces) into ½cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}, cut lengthways into 1cm strips, then chop into 1cm chunks. Once the kettle has boiled, pour the @water{300%ml} into a #measuring jug{} with the @vegetable stock powder{1%tsp} and stir to dissolve.

Heat a splash of oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the onion and cook until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and @Sri Lankan curry powder{3/4%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more, then add the @basmati rice{150%g} and stir. Add the courgette and stock. Bring to the boil then pop a #lid{} on. Reduce the heat to low and simmer for ~{10%minutes}. Remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Zest the @lemon{1} and squeeze its juice. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Put half the parsley in a large #bowl{} and add a pinch of lemon zest and the @olive oil{1.5%tbsp}.

Peel and coarsely grate the @beetroot{1}. Add it to the bowl with the parsley dressing and pour in half the lemon juice. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Taste and add more salt, pepper, juice or zest as you desire.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. When hot, add the @king prawns{150%g}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and a little lemon juice and cook, stirring occasionally, ~{5%minutes}.

> The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Stir the prawns into the pilaf, squeeze in a little more lemon juice and add the remaining parsley. Taste the pilaf and season with more salt, pepper or lemon juice if you like. Serve a generous amount for each person - making sure the prawns are evenly distributed! Add some beetroot and herb slaw on the side. Enjoy!